structured_data.name: Evolución de la demanda - Demanda 2024
structured_data.method_of_access: Web interface query with link to detailed data access portal (ree.es/datos)
structured_data.data_format: Interactive charts, data tables, web interface
structured_data.description: Annual and monthly electricity demand evolution report for Spain covering 2024, provided by Red Eléctrica de España (REE). The dataset includes total national demand (248,811 GWh in 2024), peninsular system demand (233,462 GWh), and regional breakdown by autonomous communities. Covers electricity generation mix including renewable sources (hydroelectric, wind, solar photovoltaic, solar thermal), nuclear, combined cycle, coal, and other sources. Data is provisional as of January 2025 with annual updates. Includes energy balance information, demand coverage analysis, and storage/battery integration data.
structured_data.granularity: National (Spain), regional (Autonomous Communities), and subsystem level (Peninsular, Balearic Islands, Canary Islands, Ceuta, Melilla)

structured_data.name: National Inventory Submissions 2023 - Annex I Party GHG Inventory Submissions
structured_data.method_of_access: Web interface with downloadable files (NIR and CRF tables); data accessible through UNFCCC website with links to individual party submissions
structured_data.data_format: National Inventory Report (NIR) and Common Reporting Format (CRF) tables; supplementary information in Standard Electronic Format (SEF)
structured_data.description: Annual greenhouse gas inventory submissions from Annex I parties to the UNFCCC for 2023, containing detailed descriptive and numerical information on GHG emissions and removals. Includes National Inventory Reports (NIRs) with comprehensive data, Common Reporting Format (CRF) tables with emissions, removals, implied emission factors and activity data, and supplementary Kyoto Protocol information. Provider: UNFCCC Secretariat. Time period: 2023 submission year covering historical data. Update frequency: Annual submissions.

structured_data.name: ESIOS - Sistema de Información del Operador del Sistema (Generation and Consumption Data)
structured_data.description: ESIOS is the Information System of the Spanish electricity system operator (Red Eléctrica de España - REE). The platform provides real-time and historical data on electricity generation and consumption in Spain. The content shows updates to technical specifications, operational procedures, and service documentation related to grid management, demand response services, and voltage control. Updates are published regularly with the most recent entries from 2025.

structured_data.name: Estadística de Consumo Energético Residencial Anual
structured_data.method_of_access: Web interface with links to results and methodology documentation; data accessible through the Ministry of Ecological Transition and Demographic Challenge (MITECO) website
structured_data.description: Annual statistical operation providing information on energy consumption in the residential sector in Spain by end-use categories. The dataset analyzes various energy sources (electricity, petroleum products, coal, natural gas, renewable sources, waste, and heat pumps) and primary end-uses (space heating, space cooling, water heating, cooking, lighting, electrical appliances, and other final uses). Provider: Ministry of Ecological Transition and Demographic Challenge (MITECO). Update frequency: Annual. Time period: Ongoing annual collection.

decision_log.summary: Reviewed 5 documents from Spanish energy and climate sources. Three documents show strong promise for GHGI data extraction: REE's electricity demand statistics (comprehensive energy data with tables and historical series), UNFCCC's national inventory submissions portal (direct access to Spain's official GHG inventories), and IDAE's energy statistics and balances (detailed sectoral energy data 1990-2023). MITECO's residential energy consumption statistics and ESIOS's generation/consumption portal are relevant but more narrowly focused. Overall, this is a high-quality batch with multiple authoritative sources.
decision_log.reasoning: Multiple authoritative Spanish government sources (REE, IDAE, MITECO) and the UNFCCC portal identified with clear evidence of structured energy and emissions data. REE provides electricity demand data with historical tables (2014-2024); IDAE offers comprehensive energy balances (1990-2023) covering primary and final energy by sector; MITECO provides residential consumption statistics; and UNFCCC is the official repository for Spain's national GHG inventory submissions. These sources directly support stationary_energy sector analysis. The ESIOS portal appears to be primarily operational/technical rather than data-focused, so excluded from extraction priority.

decision_log.summary: Excellent collection of authoritative Spanish GHGI sources. The extracted data includes Spain's official UNFCCC National Inventory Submissions (NIR/CRF tables), government statistical data on residential energy consumption from MITECO, and real-time electricity system data from REE. All sources are credible government institutions or official UNFCCC submissions. The data covers multiple GHGI sectors (stationary energy, residential buildings) with national-level granularity appropriate for inventory purposes. Minor limitation: electricity generation data is more detailed than direct GHG emissions data in current extractions, but the UNFCCC NIR submission should contain comprehensive emissions factors and activity data.
decision_log.reasoning: This is a strong collection of official Spanish GHGI sources that meets all acceptance criteria: (1) Official national GHGI activity data is available through UNFCCC submissions; (2) Government statistical office data (MITECO) is available for the residential sector; (3) Key emission categories are covered (energy industries, residential buildings, electricity); (4) All sources are from credible government institutions with statutory responsibility for these data; (5) National-level data is appropriate for GHGI purposes and is available from authoritative sources. The search plan has successfully identified the primary sources needed for Spanish residential sector GHG emissions inventory work. No deep dive is needed as the sources are clearly identified and accessible. The UNFCCC NIR submission in particular is the definitive source for Spain's official GHGI.
